window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2012>1>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2012","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"FLUID AT REST : EQUILIBRIUM OF BODIES: ARCHIMEDES\u2019 PRINCIPLE","question":"Study the diagrams above and use them as guides in carrying out the following instructions .  (i) Using the spring balance provided, determine the weight of object of mass M = 50.0 g in air Record this weight as W1.  (ii) Determine the weight of the object when it is completely immersed in water contained in a beaker at shown in the diagram above. Record the weight W2  .  (iii) Determine the weight of the object when it Is completely immersed in the liquid labelled L. Record the weight as W3.  (iv)  Evaluate U = (W1 - W2) and V = (W1 \u2013  W3).  (v) Repeat the procedure with the objects of masses M = 100 g, 150 g, 200 g and 250 g.  (vi)  In each case, evaluate U = (W1 - W2) and V = (W1 -  W3).  (vii) Tabulate your readings.  (viii) Plot a graph with V on the vertical axis and U on the horizontal axis.  (ix) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.  (x) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results. [21 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"M(g)W1(N)W2(N)W3(N)U = (W1 - W2)(N)V = (W1 - W3)(N)500.500.450.470.050.031001.000.900.940.100.061501.501.301.340.200.162002.001.701.740.300.262502.502.102.140.400.36        slope, s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.32\u22120.080.36\u22120.11\\frac{0.32-0.08}{0.36-0.11}0.36\u22120.110.32\u22120.08\u200b = 0.240.25\\frac{0.24}{0.25}0.250.24\u200b = 0.96    Precautions:  1. I carefully avoided parallax error by ensuring that I read the spring balance at eye level.    2. I checked for and corrected any zero error on the spring balance before taking measurements.    3. I handled the liquid carefully to avoid splashing, which could affect measurement accuracy.    4. I ensured that the object did not touch the bottom or sides of the beaker to maintain accurate buoyancy readings.    5. I thoroughly cleaned the mass before dipping it into the liquid to prevent contamination or unwanted reactions.    6. I repeated each measurement and recorded multiple readings in the table to ensure accuracy and reliability.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2012>1>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2012","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"FLUID AT REST : EQUILIBRIUM OF BODIES: ARCHIMEDES\u2019 PRINCIPLE","question":"State Archimedes' principle. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Archimedes' Principle states that any object, partially or fully submerged in a fluid, experiences an upward buoyant force (upthrust) equal to the weight of the fluid displaced by the object.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2012>1>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2012","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"FLUID AT REST : EQUILIBRIUM OF BODIES: ARCHIMEDES\u2019 PRINCIPLE","question":"A piece of brass of mass 20.0 g is hung on a spring balance from a rigid support and completely immersed in kerosene of density 8.0 \u00d7 102 kgm-3. Determine the reading on the spring balance. (g = 10 ms-2, density of brass = 8.0 \u00d7 103 kgm-3) [2 marks]    (Provide your answer to 2 d.p and with the unit e.g 123.123 m)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"mass of brass = 20g = 0.02 kg    Density of Kerosene = 8 x 102 kgm-3    g = 10 ms-2    Weight of the brass in air:    W = m \u00d7 g = 0.02 \u00d7 10 = 0.2 N    Calculating the Upthrust, U    U = density of kerosene \u00d7 Volume of brass immersed \u00d7 g    sincevolume,V,ofbrass=mass of brassdensity of brass  \u2234U=densityofkerosene\u00d7mass of brassdensity of brass\u00d7g  U=8.0 \u00d7 102\u00d70.028.0 \u00d7 103\u00d710  U = 0.02 N    The reading on the spring balance = W - U = 0.2 - 0.02 = 0.18 N","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2012>2>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2012","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"FLUID AT REST : PRESSURE IN FLUIDS","question":"You are provided with a syringe, a petri-dish firmly attached to the base of the movable piston (Plunger) of the syringe, a set of weights and other necessary apparatus.  (i) Pull the piston of the syringe upward until it can no longer move.  Read and record this position of the piston on the graduated mark on the syringe as Vo.  (ii) Clamp the syringe and ensure that it is vertical.  (iii) Place a mass M = 500 g gently at the centre of the petri-dish  (iv)  Read and record the new position of the piston as V.  (v) Evaluate V-1.  (vi) Repeat the procedure for four other values of M = 1000 g, 1500 g, 2000 g and 2500 g.  (vii) Tabulate your readings.  (viii) Plot a graph with V-1 on the vertical axis and M on the horizontal axis, starting both axes from the origin (0, 0).  (ix) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.  (x) Evaluate k = s-1  (xi) State two precautions taken to ensure accurate results. [21 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"M(g)V(cm)V-1(cm-1)50018.180.055100012.190.08215009.090.11020007.140.14025005.880.170        slope, s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.16\u22120.062375\u2212625\\frac{0.16-0.06}{2375-625}2375\u22126250.16\u22120.06\u200b = 0.11750\\frac{0.1}{1750}17500.1\u200b = 0.000057    k = s-1 = 1s\\frac{1}{s}s1\u200b = 15.7\u00d710\u22125\\frac{1}{5.7\u00d710^{-5}}5.7\u00d710\u221251\u200b = 17500    Precautions:  1. I verified that both the syringe and weights were properly calibrated before starting the experiment to ensure accurate measurements.    2. I securely attached the petri dish to the plunger to prevent any shifting during the experiment.    3. I ensured that the setup was on a stable, flat surface to minimize vibrations or unintended movement that could affect the results.    4. I checked for any air bubbles in the syringe to avoid errors in volume measurement.    5. I repeated each measurement multiple times and averaged the results to increase reliability and accuracy in the experiment.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2012>2>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2012","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"FLUID AT REST : PRESSURE IN FLUIDS","question":"When a weight is placed on the petri-dish, which quantities of the gas in the syringe (a) increases; (b) decreases? [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"When a weight is placed on the petri dish:    (a) The pressure of the gas in the syringe increases because the added weight applies a force on the gas, compressing it.    (b) The volume of the gas in the syringe decreases as it is compressed under the added pressure.    This relationship follows Boyle's Law, which states that for a fixed amount of gas at a constant temperature, the pressure and volume are inversely proportional.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2012>2>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2012","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"FLUID AT REST : PRESSURE IN FLUIDS","question":"What is responsible for the pressure exerted by a gas in a closed vessel? [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The pressure exerted by a gas in a closed vessel is due to the continuous collisions of gas molecules with the walls of the vessel. As gas molecules move randomly at high speeds, they strike the vessel walls, and each collision exerts a small force. The collective impact of these collisions over the surface area of the walls creates the observable pressure of the gas.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2012>3>a","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2012","type":"Practical","sub_label":"a","group":"CLOSENESS","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : CURRENT ELECTRICITY","question":"You are provided with a potentiometer, an ammeter, a voltmeter, standard resistor and other necessary apparatus. Using the circuit diagram above as a guide, carry out the following instructions.    (i) Set up a circuit as illustrated in the diagram above.  (ii) Close the key, K.  (iii)  Read and record the ammeter reading lo and the voltmeter reading Vo when jockey J is not making contact with the potentiometer wire OQ  (iv) Using J, make a contact with the potentiometer wire OQ at a point P such that OP = 10 cm  (v) Read and record the current I and the corresponding value of the voltage V.  (vi)  Repeat the procedure for other values of OP = 20 cm, 30 cm, 40 cm, 50 cm and 60 cm.  (vii) Tabulate your readings.  (viii)  Plot a graph with V on the vertical axis and I on the horizontal axis, starting both axes from the origin (0,0).  (ix) Determine the slope, s, of the graph.  (x) Determine the value of V when I = 0.  (xi) State two precautions taken to obtain accurate results. [21 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Table of values/ observations    OP(cm)I(A)V(V)10.00.660.6820.00.680.5830.000.700.4840.000.720.3850.000.760.1860.000.760.18        slope, s = y2\u2212y1x2\u2212x1\\frac{y_{2}-y_{1}}{x_{2}-x_{1}}x2\u200b\u2212x1\u200by2\u200b\u2212y1\u200b\u200b = 0.68\u22120.180.66\u22120.76\\frac{0.68-0.18}{0.66-0.76}0.66\u22120.760.68\u22120.18\u200b = 0.5\u22120.1\\frac{0.5}{-0.1}\u22120.10.5\u200b = -5    Equation of the line is:    -5 = V\u22120.68I\u22120.66\\frac{V-0.68}{I-0.66}I\u22120.66V\u22120.68\u200b (from m = y\u2212y1x\u2212x1\\frac{y-y_{1}}{x-x_{1}}x\u2212x1\u200by\u2212y1\u200b\u200b)    V - 0.68 = -5I + 3.3    V = -5I + 3.98    When I = 0,    V = -5(0) + 3.98    \u2234 V = 3.98 V    Precautions:  1. I ensured the key was opened whenever readings were not being taken to prevent unnecessary battery drain and maintain circuit stability.    2. I avoided parallax error by reading the ammeter and voltmeter scales directly at eye level to ensure accurate measurements.    3. I checked for and corrected any zero error on the ammeter and voltmeter before starting the experiment for improved accuracy.    4. I made sure all terminals were clean and tightly connected to prevent resistance issues and current fluctuations.    5. I carefully placed the jockey on the potentiometer wire without sliding or dragging it to avoid damaging the wire and ensure consistent contact.    6. I verified that all instruments were properly calibrated prior to use to enhance the reliability of the results.","marks":"21","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2012>3>b>i","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2012","type":"Practical","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"State two advantages of a lead-acid accumulator over a dry Leclanche cell. [2 marks]","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Here are several advantages of a lead-acid accumulator over a dry Leclanche cell:    1. Higher Capacity: Lead-acid accumulators can deliver a larger amount of current over a longer period, making them suitable for high-demand applications.    2. Rechargeable: Lead-acid accumulators are rechargeable and can endure multiple charge-discharge cycles, whereas Leclanche cells are generally single-use and non-rechargeable.    3. Lower Internal Resistance: This allows lead-acid accumulators to deliver higher currents more efficiently, reducing energy loss compared to Leclanche cells.    4. Longer Shelf Life: Lead-acid accumulators tend to have a longer lifespan if maintained properly, while Leclanche cells degrade faster over time.    5. Consistent Voltage Output: Lead-acid accumulators provide a more stable voltage throughout their discharge cycle, whereas the voltage of a Leclanche cell drops significantly as it discharges.    These characteristics make lead-acid accumulators more suitable for applications that require sustained and reliable power output.","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Physics Practical>2012>3>b>ii","subject":"Physics Practical","year":"2012","type":"Practical","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"ELECTRIC FIELD : ELECTRIC CURRENT, POTENTIAL DIFFERENCE, RESISTANCE, E.M.F. AND INTERNAL RESISTANCE","question":"A cell of emf 2 V and internal resistance of 1 \u03a9 passes current through an external load of 9 \u03a9. Calculate the potential drop across the cell. [2 marks]    (Provide your answer to 1 d.p and with the unit e.g 123.123 m)","images":["data:image/jpeg;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"emf, E = 2 \u03a9    Internal resistance, r = 1 \u03a9    External resistance, R = 9 \u03a9    E = l(R + r)    2 = I(9 + 1)    2 = 10I    \u2234 the current, I = 0.2 A    The potential drop across the cell's internal resistance:    \u2234 V = IR = 0.2 \u00d7 1 = 0.2 V","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"}];